04767nam a22006975i 9780271098180DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232024pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710981807 a10.1515/97802710981802doi  a(DE-B1597)680243  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aNA9274.7.M37 7aARC0050302bisacsh04a711/.4096464223/eng/202311031 aStockstill, Abbey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMarrakesh and the Mountains :bLandscape, Urban Planning, and Identity in the Medieval Maghrib /cAbbey Stockstill. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2023] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (168 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBuildings, Landscapes, and Societies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Translation, Transliteration, and Dynastic Terminology -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 Almoravid Foundations -- tChapter 2 Almohad Renovation -- tChapter 3 Almohad Urbanism Elsewhere: Seville and Rabat -- tEpilogue: The Genius Loci of Marrakesh -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the course of the Almoravid (1040–1147) and Almohad (1121–1269) dynasties, medieval Marrakesh evolved from an informal military encampment into a thriving metropolis that attempted to translate a local and distinctly rural past into a broad, imperial architectural vernacular. In Marrakesh and the Mountains, Abbey Stockstill convincingly demonstrates that the city’s surrounding landscape provided the principal mode of negotiation between these identities.The contours of medieval Marrakesh were shaped in the twelfth-century transition between the two empires of Berber origin. These dynasties constructed their imperial authority through markedly different approaches to urban space, reflecting their respective concerns in communicating complex identities that fluctuated between paradigmatically Islamic and distinctly local. Using interdisciplinary methodologies to reconstruct this urban environment, Stockstill broadens the analysis of Marrakesh’s medieval architecture to explore the interrelated interactions among the city’s monuments and its highly resonant landscape. Marrakesh and the Mountains integrates Marrakesh into the context of urbanism in the wider Islamic world and grants the Almoravid and Almohad dynasties agency over the creation and instantiation of their imperial capital.Lushly illustrated and erudite, Marrakesh and the Mountains is a vital history of this storied Moroccan city. This is a must-have book for scholars specializing in the Almoravid and Almohad eras and a vital volume for students of medieval urbanism, Islamic architecture, and Mediterranean and African studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAlmohadeszMoroccozMarrakechxHistory. 0aAlmoravideszMoroccozMarrakechxHistory. 0aArchitecture, MedievalzMoroccozMarrakech. 0aCity planningzMoroccozMarrakechxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aIslamic architecturezMoroccozMarrakechxHistoryyTo 1500. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAlmohad.  aAlmoravid.  aIslamic architecture.  aMaghrib.  aMoroccan archaeology.  aMoroccan architecture.  aNorth Africa.  aarchitectural history.  alandscape studies.  amedieval Islam.  amedieval Mediterranean.  amedieval urbanism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079776340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271098180?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271098180423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271098180/original  a978-3-11-079776-3  Penn State Universi